<node id="Matrix">
  <data key="d0">Matrix</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A matrix is a mathematical entity defined as a rectangular array of numbers or other mathematical objects, organized in rows and columns. This two-dimensional structure plays a crucial role in various mathematical computations and applications, making it fundamental to fields such as linear algebra.

Matrices can contain numbers or functions and are often represented using upper-case variable names. They are essential for performing mathematical operations, including solving systems of equations, transforming data, and representing relationships in various computations. Due to their structured format, matrices facilitate efficient data organization and manipulation.

In summary, the matrix stands as a significant mathematical structure, utilized broadly for various applications in mathematics and computational fields, providing tools for analysis and representation of complex data.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1cab33350eba1be65fc00415923198c9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-88935c9c850ad773b6af22d7912a351e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f81436ceefbaa6d5dc02610dd8127f9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0403607cb7181d4a13a232d13fec9630&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0d55b6724597822ab76201288059bd8f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e325d64a50359748cfb47987a361fbb1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9c074e64b3d10aa196769e1082af2cbd</data>
