<node id="Eigenvalues">
  <data key="d0">Eigenvalues</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Eigenvalues are scalars that indicate how much the corresponding eigenvector is stretched or compressed during a matrix transformation.&lt;SEP&gt;Eigenvalues are scalar values associated with a linear transformation represented by a square matrix, indicating the factor by which the corresponding eigenvector is scaled.&lt;SEP&gt;Eigenvalues are scalar values associated with a matrix that help in understanding its properties and behavior during decomposition.&lt;SEP&gt;Eigenvalues are scalar values that provide information about the scaling factor of eigenvectors during linear transformations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f81436ceefbaa6d5dc02610dd8127f9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-443f6360d2d3fc61bef3f5a8c109e2f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136818</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Eigenvectors">
  <data key="d0">Eigenvectors</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Eigenvectors are special vectors associated with a matrix that remain in the same direction after the matrix transformation, only scaled by a corresponding eigenvalue.&lt;SEP&gt;Eigenvectors are non-zero vectors associated with a matrix that indicate directions in which the matrix acts by scaling.&lt;SEP&gt;Eigenvectors are non-zero vectors that change by only a scalar factor when a matrix is applied to them, playing a key role in eigendecomposition.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f81436ceefbaa6d5dc02610dd8127f9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136818</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Real Symmetric Matrix">
  <data key="d0">Real Symmetric Matrix</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A real symmetric matrix is a square matrix that is equal to its transpose, allowing for a specific type of eigendecomposition.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f81436ceefbaa6d5dc02610dd8127f9b</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136818</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Eigendecomposition">
  <data key="d0">Eigendecomposition</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Eigendecomposition is a technique in Linear Algebra used to express a matrix in terms of its eigenvalues and eigenvectors, important for dimensionality reduction techniques in machine learning.&lt;SEP&gt;Eigendecomposition refers to the process of analyzing a matrix to determine its eigenvalues and eigenvectors, applicable only to square matrices.&lt;SEP&gt;Eigendecomposition is a matrix decomposition method that expresses a matrix in terms of its eigenvalues and eigenvectors.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f81436ceefbaa6d5dc02610dd8127f9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d9a143ce5c66baaa2cee5e90f9622516&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136818</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)">
  <data key="d0">Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">SVD is a matrix factorization method that allows for decomposing a matrix into its singular values and vectors, applicable to all real matrices.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f81436ceefbaa6d5dc02610dd8127f9b</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136818</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
