  <data key="d0">SVD</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) is a mathematical technique used for decomposing a matrix into its constituent parts, applicable to all real matrices.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136831</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Matrix Inversion">
  <data key="d0">Matrix Inversion</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Matrix inversion is a mathematical concept that allows for the solving of matrix equations.&lt;SEP&gt;Matrix inversion is the process of finding the inverse of a square matrix, which is used to solve systems of linear equations when applicable.&lt;SEP&gt;Matrix inversion is a mathematical operation defined for square matrices, used to find a matrix that, when multiplied by the original matrix, yields the identity matrix.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e325d64a50359748cfb47987a361fbb1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9c074e64b3d10aa196769e1082af2cbd</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136831</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Pseudoinverse">
  <data key="d0">Pseudoinverse</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The pseudoinverse is a generalization of the matrix inverse, defined for non-square matrices, enabling the solution of linear equations where traditional matrix inversion is not applicable.&lt;SEP&gt;The pseudoinverse is a generalization of the matrix inverse used for solving linear equations when matrices are not square.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-443f6360d2d3fc61bef3f5a8c109e2f2</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136832</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Diagonal Matrix">
  <data key="d0">Diagonal Matrix</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A diagonal matrix is a type of matrix where all entries outside the main diagonal are zero, and it is used in various matrix operations including pseudoinverse calculations.&lt;SEP&gt;A diagonal matrix is a matrix in which the elements outside the main diagonal are all zero, with significant properties in linear algebra.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-443f6360d2d3fc61bef3f5a8c109e2f2</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136832</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Orthogonal Matrices">
  <data key="d0">Orthogonal Matrices</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Orthogonal matrices are square matrices whose rows and columns are mutually orthonormal, allowing for simple computations of their inverses.&lt;SEP&gt;Orthogonal matrices are square matrices whose rows and columns are orthogonal unit vectors, retaining certain properties during transformations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136832</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
