<node id="Vectors">
  <data key="d0">Vectors</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Vectors are mathematical entities that can be compared based on their norms and angles relative to each other.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136845</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Orthogonality">
  <data key="d0">Orthogonality</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Orthogonality refers to the relationship between vectors that are at 90 degrees to each other, typically characterized by a dot product of zero.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136845</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Matrix Decomposition">
  <data key="d0">Matrix Decomposition</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Matrix decomposition involves breaking down a matrix into constituent parts to reveal functional properties or simpler representations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136845</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Unit Eigenvectors">
  <data key="d0">Unit Eigenvectors</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Unit eigenvectors are eigenvectors that have been normalized to have a norm of one, simplifying calculations and analysis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770136845</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
